Overview

Every distribution that R handles has four functions. There is a root name, for example norm, the root name for the normal distribution is norm. This root is prefixed by one of the letters

  • p for âprobabilityâ, the cumulative distribution function
  • q for âquantileâ, the inverse cumulative distribution function
  • d for âdensityâ, the density function
  • r for ârandomâ, a random variable having the specified distribution

For a continuous distribution, the most useful functions for doing problems involving probability calculations are the âpâ and âqâ functions (cumulative distribution function and the inverse cumulative distribution functions, because the the density calculated by the âdâ function can only be used to calculate probabilities via integrals and R doesnât do integrals.

For a discrete distribution (like the binomial), the âdâ function calculates the density, which in this case is a probability \(f(x) = P(X = x)\) and hence is useful in calculating probabilities.

The p functions have the logical parameter lower.tail. If TRUE probabilites are \(P(X \le x)\), otherwise \(P(X>x)\). The q functions have the same parameter with the corresponding meaning.

Arbitrary discrete distribution from a sample

  obs = sort(unique(dat)),
  abs = table(dat),
  rel = abs/length(dat),
  cum = cumsum(rel)

pdat <- function(x, lower.tail = TRUE) {
  if (lower.tail == TRUE) return(H(x))
  else return(1-H(x))
}
ddat <- function(x) {
  res <- rep(NA, length(x))
  for (i in 1:length(x)) {
    if (x[i] %in% freq.tab$obs) 
      res[i] <- freq.tab$rel[which(freq.tab$obs == x[i])]
    else res[i] <- 0
  }
  return(res)
}

Uniform Distributions

The corresponding functions for the discrete uniform distributions are not part of the base package. They are implemented in the package âextrDistâ

Example: rolling a fair die

# load the library extraDistr
library(extraDistr)
## Warning: package 'extraDistr' was built under R version 4.0.5
## 
## Attaching package: 'extraDistr'
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
## 
##     rdunif
# example rolling a fair die
a <- 1
b <- 6

barplot(ddunif(a:b,a,b),
        names.arg = a:b,
        main = "density discrete uniform distribution")

plot(x = seq(0,10,by=0.1), y = pdunif(seq(0,10,by=0.1),a,b),
     xlab = "x", ylab = "probability",
     main = "distribution function")

plot(x = seq(0,1,by=0.01), y = qdunif(seq(0,1,by=0.01),a,b),
     xlab = "p", ylab = "p quantile",
     main = "quantiles")

rdunif(100,a,b) %>% table() 
## .
##  1  2  3  4  5  6 
## 16 17 20 17 14 16

Implementation of own functions

# ddunifdisc(x, min, max)
# pdunifdisc(q, min, max, lower.tail = TRUE)
# qdunidisc(p, min, max, lower.tail = TRUE)
# rdunifdisc(n, min, max)
# Arguments:
# x, q : numerical value
# min, max : lower and upper limits of the distribution. Must be an integer.
# p : probability
# n : number of observations

dunifdisc <-  function(x, min, max) {
  result <- rep(NA,length(x))
  for (i in 1:length(x)) {
    if (x[i]>=min & x[i]<=max & round(x[i])==x[i])  
      result[i] <- 1/(max-min+1)
    else result[i] <- 0
  }
  return(result)
}
punifdisc <- function(q, min, max) {
  result <- rep(NA,length(q))
  for (i in 1:length(q)) {
    if (q[i] < min) {
      result[i] <- 0
    } else {
      if (q[i] >= max) {
        result[i] <- 1
      }  else {
        result[i] <- (floor(q[i])-min+1)/(max-min+1)
      }
    }
  }
  return(result)
}
qunifdisc <- function(p, min, max) return(floor(p*(max-min+1)))
runifdisc <- function(n, min, max) return(sample(min:max, n, replace=T))

Binomial Distributions

Example: no of sixes in rolling a fair die 10 times

p <- 1/6
n <- 10

barplot(dbinom(0:10,size = n, prob = p),
        names.arg = 0:10,
        main = "density B(n=10, p=1/6) distribution")

plot(x = seq(0,10,by=0.1), 
     y = pbinom(seq(0,10,by=0.1), size = n, prob = p),
     ylim = c(0,1),
     xlab = "x", ylab = "probability",
     main = "distribution function")

plot(x = seq(0,1,by=0.0001), 
     y = qbinom(seq(0,1,by=0.0001), size = n, prob = p),
     xlab = "p", ylab = "p quantile",
     main = "quantiles")

rbinom(100,size = n, prob = p) %>% table() 
## .
##  0  1  2  3  4 
## 20 23 31 20  6

Hypergeometric Distributions

Example: no of red balls drawn withaout replacement out of an urn with 20 balls, 15 red balls an 10 drawns

M <- 15 # number of red balls
N <- 20 # total number of balls
n <- 10 # number of balls drawn
barplot(dhyper(0:10, m = M, n = N-M, k = n),
        names.arg = 0:10,
        main = "density H(N=20, M=15, n = 10) distribution")

plot(x = seq(0,10,by=0.1), 
     y = phyper(seq(0,10,by=0.1), m = M, n = N-M, k = n),
     ylim = c(0,1),
     xlab = "x", ylab = "probability",
     main = "distribution function")

plot(x = seq(0,1,by=0.0001), 
     y = qhyper(seq(0,1,by=0.0001), m = M, n = N-M, k = n),
     xlab = "p", ylab = "p quantile",
     main = "quantiles")

rhyper(100, m = M, n = N-M, k = n) %>% table() 
## .
##  6  7  8  9 10 
## 14 32 39 13  2

Uniform Distributions

Example: waiting times to a bus coming exactly every 10 minutes, if you come randomly to the bus stop

Min <- 0
Max <- 10
plot(x=seq(-1,11,by=0.1), 
     y=dunif(seq(-1,11,by=0.1),min = Min, max = Max),
     ylim = c(0,0.2),
     ylab = "", xlab = "x",
     type = "l",
     main = "density R(a=0, b=10) distribution")

plot(x = seq(-1,11,by=0.1), 
     y = punif(seq(-1,11,by=0.1), min = Min, max = Max),
     type = "l",
     xlab = "x", ylab = "probability",
     main = "distribution function")

plot(x = seq(0,1,by=0.0001), 
     y = qunif(seq(0,1,by=0.0001), min = Min, max = Max),
     xlab = "p", ylab = "p quantile",
     type = "l",
     main = "quantiles")

runif(100, min = Min, max = Max) %>% 
  cut(breaks = 0:10) %>% 
  table()

Normal distributions

Example: mu = 5, sigma = 2

s <- 2
plot(x=seq(-1,11,by=0.1), 
     y=dnorm(seq(-1,11,by=0.1), mean = mu, sd = s),
     ylab = "", xlab = "x",
     type = "l",
     main = "density N(5,2) distribution")

plot(x = seq(-1,11,by=0.1), 
     y = pnorm(seq(-1,11,by=0.1), mean = mu, sd = s),
     ylim = c(0,1),
     type = "l",
     xlab = "x", ylab = "probability",
     main = "distribution function")

plot(x = seq(0,1,by=0.0001), 
     y = qnorm(seq(0,1,by=0.0001), mean = mu, sd = s),
     xlab = "p", ylab = "p quantile",
     type = "l",
     main = "quantiles")

  table()

F Distributions

Example: degrees of freedom = (10,2)

d1 <- 10
d2 <- 2
plot(x=seq(0,5,by=0.1), 
     y=df(seq(0,5,by=0.1), df1 = d1, df2 = d2),
     type = "l", 
     ylab = "", xlab = "x",
     main = "density F distribution df = (10,2)")

plot(x = seq(0,5,by=0.1), 
     y = pf(seq(0,5,by=0.1), df1 = d1, df2 = d2),
     type = "l",
     xlab = "x", ylab = "probability",
     main = "distribution function")

plot(x = seq(0,1,by=0.0001), 
     y = qf(seq(0,1,by=0.0001), df1 = d1, df2 = d2),
     type = "l",
     ylim = c(0,100),
     xlab = "p", ylab = "p quantile",
     main = "quantiles")

rf(100, df1 = d1, df2 = d2) %>% cut(breaks = seq(0,5,by=0.25)) %>% table()
